|Moriarty}} || ''{{sort|Extremely Inconvenient Adventures of Bronte Mettlestone|The Extremely Inconvenient Adventures of Bronte Mettlestone}}'' || [[Allen & Unwin]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2017\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20172|[[2017 in literature|2017]]}} || {{sortname|Emily|Rodda}} || ''{{sort|Shop at Hoopers Bend|The Shop at Hoopers Bend}}'' || [[HarperCollins Australia]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2017\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20172|[[2017 in literature|2017]]}} || {{sortname|Jo|Sandhu}} || ''{{sort|Exile|The Exile}}'' || [[Penguin Random House Australia]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2017\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20172|[[2017 in literature|2017]]}} || {{sortname|Lian|Tanner}} || ''Accidental Heroes'' || [[Allen & Unwin]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2017\"/>\n\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20181|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || {{sortname|Penni|Russon}}* || ''{{sort|Endsister|The Endsister}}'' || [[Allen & Unwin]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2018\"/><ref name=\"AAW 2018\">{{citation | title = 2018 Aurealis Awards Winners |url=https://aurealisawards.org/2019/05/05/2018-aurealis-awards-winners/ | publisher = Continuum Foundation | date = 2019-05-05 | accessdate = 2019-05-05}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20182|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || {{sortname|Rebecca|Lim}} || ''{{sort|Relic of the Blue Dragon|The Relic of the Blue Dragon}}'' || Allen & Unwin || <ref name=\"AAF 2018\">{{citation | title = 2018 Aurealis Awards shortlist announcement! |url=https://aurealisawards.org/2019/02/20/2018-aurealis-awards-shortlist-announcement/ | publisher = Continuum Foundation | date = 2019-02-20 | accessdate = 2019-04-25}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20182|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || {{sortname|Jaclyn|Moriarty}} || ''{{sort|Slightly Alarming Tales of the Whispering Wars|The Slightly Alarming Tales of the Whispering Wars}}'' || [[Allen & Unwin]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2018\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20182|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || {{sortname|Lian|Tanner}} || ''Secret Guardians'' || [[Allen & Unwin]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2018\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20182|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || {{sortname|Gabrielle|Wang}} || ''Ting Ting the Ghosthunter'' || [[Penguin Random House Australia]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2018\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20182|[[2018 in literature|2018]]}} || {{sortname|Rhiannon|Williams}} || ''Ottilie Cotter and the Narroway Hunt'' || [[Hardie Grant Egmont]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2018\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20192|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}} || {{sortname|Amie|Kaufman}} || ''Scorch Dragons'' || [[HarperCollins]] || <ref name=\"B+P2019\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.booksandpublishing.com.au/articles/2020/03/27/148459/aurealis-awards-2019-finalists-announced/|title=Aurealis Awards 2019 finalists announced|last=|first=|date=2020-03-27|website=Books+Publishing|language=en-AU|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20192|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}} || {{sortname|Rebecca|Lim|Rebecca Lim (writer)}} || Race for the Red Dragon || [[Allen & Unwin]] ||<ref name=\"B+P2019\" />\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20192|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}} || {{sortname|Bren|MacDibble}} || ''The Dog Runner'' || [[Allen & Unwin]] || <ref name=\"B+P2019\" />\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20192|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}} || {{sortname|Rebecca|McRitchie}}, ([[Sharon O'Connor]], illustrator) || ''Jinxed! the Curious Curse of Cora Bell'' || [[HarperCollins]] || <ref name=\"B+P2019\" />\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20192|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}} || {{sortname|Emily|Rodda|Jennifer Rowe}}, ([[Marc McBride]], illustrator) || ''The Glimme'' || [[Scholastic Corporation|Scholastic]] || <ref name=\"B+P2019\" />\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20192|[[2019 in literature|2019]]}} || {{sortname|Heather|Waugh}} || ''The Lost Stone of SkyCity'' || [[Fremantle Press]] || <ref name=\"B+P2019\" />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://aurealisawards.org/ Aurealis Awards official site]\n\n{{Aurealis Awards}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Aurealis Award For Best Children's Book}}\n[[Category:Australian children's literary awards]]\n[[Category:Aurealis Awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox award\n| name           = Aurealis Award for best children's fiction\n| current_awards =\n| image          = Aurealis Award Winner Logo.png\n| imagesize      = 119px\n| alt            = A gold colored circle with the words \"aurealis awards\" across the middle, and \"winner\" situated in the lower portion. In the top portion is a smaller black and white circle with various curving lines and a shape of an eye in the middle\n| caption        = The Aurealis Award design is often placed on the winning book's cover as a promotional tool.<ref name=\"EON HARPERCOLLINS\">{{cite web|url=http://harpercollins.com.au/books/9780732290115/Eon/index.aspx |title=Eon by Alison Goodman |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |accessdate=2010-03-30 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100221025801/http://www.harpercollins.com.au/books/9780732290115/Eon/index.aspx |archivedate=21 February 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| description    = Excellence in [[Children's literature|children's]] [[speculative fiction]]\n| presenter      = [[Chimaera Publications]],<br>Continuum Foundation\n| country        = Australia\n| location       =\n| year           = 2013 (merging two previous categories)\n| holder         = [[Penni Russon]]\n| website        = [http://aurealisawards.org/ Official site]\n}}\n\nThe [[Aurealis Awards]] are presented annually by the Australia-based [[Chimaera Publications]] and WASFF to published works in order to \"recognise the achievements of Australian [[science fiction]], [[fantasy]], [[Horror fiction|horror]] writers\".<ref name=\"AAAU\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/AboutUs.htm |title=Aurealis Awards \u2013 About Us |publisher=[[Aurealis Awards]] |accessdate=2010-01-20 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rznEali0?url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/AboutUs.htm |archivedate=15 August 2010 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> To qualify, a work must have been first published by an Australian citizen or permanent resident between 1 January and 31 December of the corresponding year;<ref name=\"AARAC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/Rules.htm#Entries |title=Aurealis Awards \u2013 Rules and Conditions |publisher=[[Aurealis Awards]] |accessdate=2009-11-08 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67lwTvAyo?url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/Rules.htm#Entries |archivedate=19 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> the presentation ceremony is held the following year. It has grown from a small function of around 20 people to a two-day event attended by over 200 people.<ref name=\"NEWSAU HAT\">{{cite web | url = http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,21153270-5003424,00.html | title = Horror a hit | publisher = [[Queensland Newspapers]] | work = [[The Courier-Mail]] | date = 2007-02-02 |first = Jason |last = Nahrung | accessdate = 2009-12-01}}</ref>\n\nSince their creation in 1995, awards have been given in various categories of [[speculative fiction]]. Categories currently include science fiction, fantasy, horror, speculative [[young adult fiction]]\u2014with separate awards for novels and [[short fiction]]\u2014collections, [[anthologies]], illustrative works or [[graphic novel]]s, children's books, and an award for excellence in speculative fiction.<ref name=\"AAAU\"/> The awards have attracted the attention of publishers by setting down a benchmark in science fiction and fantasy. The continued sponsorship by publishers such as [[HarperCollins]] and [[Orbit Books|Orbit]] has identified the award as an honour to be taken seriously.<ref name=\"ABCR SOPFW\">{{cite video |people = Koval, Ramona (presenter) |date = 2009-02-05 |title = Spotlight on speculative fiction writers |url = http://www.abc.net.au/rn/bookshow/stories/2009/2483009.htm |format = mp3  |time = 1:18\u20132:16 |medium = Radio broadcast |publisher = [[ABC Radio and Regional Content]]}}</ref>\n\nThe results are decided by a panel of judges from a list of submitted nominees; the long-list of nominees is reduced to a short-list of finalists.<ref name=\"AAAU\"/> Ties can occur if the panel decides both entries show equal merit, however they are encouraged to choose a single winner.<ref name=\"AA GFJ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/downloads/guidelines-for-judges.doc |title=Guidelines for Judges |publisher=[[Aurealis Awards]] |accessdate=2009-04-23 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ogpp9ixO?url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/downloads/guidelines-for-judges.doc |archivedate=2 April 2010 }}</ref> The judges may declare a \"no award\" if there is unanimous agreement that none of the nominees are worthy.<ref name=\"AA GFJ\"/> The judges are selected from a public application process by the Award's management team.<ref name=\"AAFAQ\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/FAQ.htm |title=Aurealis Awards \u2013 FAQ |publisher=[[Aurealis Awards]] |accessdate=2009-12-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100114094938/http://www.aurealisawards.com/FAQ.htm |archivedate=14 January 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThis article lists all the short-list nominees and winners in the best children's fiction category which replaces the following two previous categories for children's fiction:\n* [[Aurealis Award for best children's fiction (told primarily through words)]]\n* [[Aurealis Award for best children's fiction (told primarily through pictures)]]\n\nIn 2013, this award was known as the Aurealis Award for best children's book.\n\n==Winners and nominees==\nIn the following table, the years correspond to the year of the work's eligibility; the ceremonies are always held the following year. Each year links to the corresponding \"year in literature\" article. Entries with a blue background have won the award; those with a white background are the nominees on the short-list. If the work was originally published in a book with other stories rather than by itself or in a magazine, the book title is included after the publisher's name.\n\n{{color box|#B0C4DE| * |Black}} Winners and joint winners<br />\n{{color box|#f9f9f9| * |#f9f9f9}} Nominees on the shortlist\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"width:85%; margin:1em auto 1em auto;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\"|Year\n! style=\"width:22.5%;\"|Author(s)\n! style=\"width:28%;\"|Work(s)\n! style=\"width:22.5%;\"|Publisher\n! style=\"width:5%;\" class=\"unsortable\"|Ref\n|- style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\"\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20131|[[2013 in literature|2013]]}} || {{sortname|Kirsty|Murray}}* || ''{{sort|Four Seasons of Lucy McKenzie|The Four Seasons of Lucy McKenzie}}'' || [[Allen & Unwin]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aurealisawards.com/Media%20Release%20-%20Finalists%20Feb%202014.pdf |title=2013 Aurealis Awards finalists announced |publisher=Conflux |accessdate=2014-03-15 |format=PDF |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140315100521/http://www.aurealisawards.com/Media%20Release%20-%20Finalists%20Feb%202014.pdf |archivedate=15 March 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"AAW 2013\">{{cite web | url = http://www.aurealisawards.com | title = 2013 Aurealis Awards Winners | publisher = Conflux | date =  | accessdate = 2014-04-07 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080206045120/http://www.aurealisawards.com/ | archive-date = 6 February 2008 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20132|[[2013 in literature|2013]]}} || {{sortname|Isobelle|Carmody}} || ''Kingdom of the Lost, book 2: Cloud Road'' || [[Penguin Books Australia]] || <ref name=\"AAF 2013\"/>\n|-\n| align=\"center\" |{{sort|20132|[[2013 